Notebook structure¶

Objective - what is our task?¶

This work attempts to propose an investment strategy, implement it and discuss the results. In particular we try to:

  1. Process the data: import the given data and identify potential missing entries
  2. Describe the data: understand the given features and create some more
  3. Design a strategy: come up with a prediction model and an investment mechanism
  4. Test and observe results: test the strategy and display results
  5. Provide a conclusion: a summary of my attempts and potential openings

II-B) Defining a Target¶

We choose an investment horizon of 1 day.

We want to use info up to day $d$. So we adjust position at close on day $d+1$ and we exit position at close on day $d+2$.

So the performance we are interested to predict is:

$$ \forall s \text{ stock}, \quad \forall d \text{ day}, \quad perf(s,d) = \frac{Price(s,d+2) - Price(s,d+1)}{Price(s,d+1)} $$

The target we are intersted to predict is thus the overperformance of a given stock with respect to the market:

$$ \forall s \text{ stock}, \quad \forall d \text{ day}, \quad overperf(s,d) = perf(s,d) - \sum_{s'} perf(s',d) $$

We note that this function is not known at day $d$ and cannot be used for in-sample analysis.

In [17]:
# Compute overperf to serve as target
target = (rdf["last"].shift(-2)-rdf["last"].shift(-1)) / rdf["last"].shift(-1)
target = target - target.mean(axis=1).values[:, None]
target.columns = pd.MultiIndex.from_tuples([("target", tick) for tick in target.columns])
target.head()

II-C) Volatility and Return features¶

Features must be known at day $d$. The earliest accessible value of $overperf5$ for a given stock is:

$$ \forall s \text{ stock}, \quad \forall d \text{ day}, \quad realized\_overperf(s,d) = overperf(s, d-2) $$
In [19]:
# Compute realized_overperf5 to serve as target
realized = (rdf["last"]-rdf["last"].shift(2)) / rdf["last"].shift(2)
realized = realized - realized.mean(axis=1).values[:, None]
realized.columns = pd.MultiIndex.from_tuples([("realized_overperf", tick) for tick in realized.columns])

# Create previous days realized_overperf features
def realized_overperf_prev(lag):
    rop = realized["realized_overperf"].shift(lag)
    rop.columns = pd.MultiIndex.from_tuples([(f"realized_overperf_lag{lag}", tick) for tick in rop.columns])
    return rop

# yesterday perf
rop = realized_overperf_prev(1)

# Create volatility features
def vol(nb_days):
    vol = realized["realized_overperf"].rolling(nb_days).std()
    vol.columns = pd.MultiIndex.from_tuples([(f"vol{nb_days}", tick) for tick in vol.columns])
    return vol

#20 day volatility of perf5
vol20 = vol(20)

II - C) Total Data and Conclusion¶

We choose to add as features, for each stock $s$, each day $d$:

  1. The $realized\_overperf(s, d')$ for $d-3 \leqslant d' \leqslant d$ ie. the most recent performance the last 3 days.
  2. The 5, 20 and 60 day volatilities of $s$

We compile everything in one data frame regrouping for each stock, each day:

  • Prices
  • Volumes
  • The target $overperf$
  • The selected features described above
In [23]:
features = [target, realized, rdf] + [realized_overperf_prev(lag) for lag in range(1,4)] + [vol(days) for days in [5,20,60]]
tdf = pd.concat(features, axis=1).stack() #tdf stands for total dataframe

               '2021-03-16', '2021-03-17'],
              dtype='datetime64[ns]', name='date', length=1942, freq=None)

III - A Long-Short Strategy¶

III - A) Cash neutral, equal weights Long-Short¶

We aim at carrying out the following Long-Short strategy.

At a given day $d_0$, compute $\hat{y}^{(d_0)} \in \mathbb{R}^{N_{stocks}}$.

Then we long stocks $s$ such that $\hat{y}^{(d_0)}_s > 0$ and short stocks such that $\hat{y}^{(d_0)}_s < 0$. If $\hat{y}^{(d_0)}_s = 0$ we take no position in $s$.

We want all long positions to be the same size in the portfolio meaning all long positions have a weight $\frac{1}{n_{buy}}$ where $n_{buy} = \sum_s \mathbb{1}(\hat{y}^{(d_0)}_s > 0)$. Same we want all short positions to be the same size. Their weight in the portfolio is $\frac{1}{n_{sell}}$ where $n_{sell} = \sum_s \mathbb{1}(\hat{y}^{(d_0)}_s < 0)$.

This allows to write the over performance of a cash neutral portfolio as a function of $overperf$: $$ portfolio\_overperf(d_0) = \frac{1}{n_{buy}} \sum_s overperf(s, d_0) \mathbb{1}(\hat{y}^{(d_0)}_s > 0) - \frac{1}{n_{sell}} \sum_s overperf(s, d_0) \mathbb{1}(\hat{y}^{(d_0)}_s < 0) $$

Next we detail how we plan to obtain $\hat{y}^{(d_0)}$.

III - B) Multivariate Linear Regression¶

We choose a lookback within a range of lookback periods (in days): 5D, 20D, 60D, 120D.

At a given day $d_0$, we fit the linear regression on the feature matrix and label vectors:

\begin{cases} X = (feature_j(s,d))_{d,s~j} \\ y = (target(s,d))_{d,s} = (overperf(s,d))_{d,s} \end{cases}

Where $s \in \text{\{stocks\}}$, $d-2 \in [d_0 - lookback, d_0]$ and $j \in [1, N_{features}]$. Both $X$ and $y$ are known at day $d_0$.

In particular $X$ is a $ (N_{stocks}~ lookback) \times N_{features}$ matrix and $y$ a $(N_{stocks}~ lookback)$ vector.

We try to find the best $\beta$ to fit the linear dependance problem $y = X \beta$ where $\beta$ is a $N_{features}$ vector. This amounts to solving the quadratic linear regression problem without intercept:

$$ \beta^* \in \arg \min_{\beta} \frac{1}{2}|| y - X \beta ||_2^2 $$

This problem admits a closed form expression for $\beta^*$ : $\beta^* = (X^T X)^{-1} X^T y $

III - C) Taking positions¶

Now consider the feature matrix at current day $d_0$:

$$ X^{(d_0)} = (feature_j(s,d_0))_{s~j} $$

Where $s \in \text{\{stocks\}}$ and $j \in [1, N_{features}]$. In particular $X^{(d_0)}$ is a $ N_{stocks} \times N_{features}$ matrix.

Using the appropriately fit $\beta^*$, compute the overperf estimator:

$$ \hat{y}^{(d_0)} = X^{(d_0)} \beta^* $$

The further loop computes $\hat{y}^{(d_0)}$ for every $d_0$ and the associated weights $\beta^*$. This loop should take around 20 minutes to run.

In [29]:
y_hat_list = []
beta_list = []
y_hat_label_list = []

lookbacks = [5, 20, 60, 120]
for lookback in tqdm.tqdm(lookbacks): # repeat for different lookbacks
    for id_day, day in enumerate(days):
        if (id_day > lookback): # need enough days in lookback
            avail_days = days[id_day+1-2-lookback:id_day+1-2] # "authorized" days to access target
            X = features.loc[avail_days, :]
            y = target.loc[avail_days, :]

            beta = np.linalg.inv(X.T @ X) @ X.T @ y # compute beta star
            beta.index = X.columns

            X_d = features.loc[day, :] # day d features
            y_hat = X_d @ beta.values

            y_hat_list.append(y_hat)
            beta_list.append(beta)
            y_hat_label_list.append((lookback, day))

y_hat = pd.concat(y_hat_list, keys=y_hat_label_list, names=["lookback", "date"])
beta = pd.concat(beta_list, keys=y_hat_label_list, names=["lookback", "date"])

The next loop computes $portfolio\_overperf(d_0)$ at each $d_0$. This should take around 6 minutes.

In [31]:
backtest_recap = []

buffer = np.zeros(len(stocks), dtype=np.float64) #serves as helper container

for lookback in tqdm.tqdm(lookbacks):
    
    days = y_hat.loc[lookback,:].index.get_level_values(1).unique() #available days depend on lookback

    for id_day, day in enumerate(days):
        y_day = y_hat.loc[lookback, day,:] #get overperf estimation across stocks at current day
        overperf_day = target.loc[day,:] #get overperf across stocks at current day

        n_buy = np.sum(y_day > 0)
        n_sell = np.sum(y_day < 0)

        buffer[:] = (y_day > 0) / n_buy - (y_day < 0) / n_sell #buffer[s] is the weight of stock s in the portfolio
        perf = np.sum(buffer * overperf_day)

        backtest_recap.append((lookback, day, perf, n_buy, n_sell))
    
backtest_recap = pd.DataFrame(backtest_recap, columns=["lookback", 'date', 'portfolio_overperf', 'nb_buy', 'nb_sell'])
backtest_recap

We see that the number of long and short positions remains relatively balanced (within 100 ± 20) across lookbacks. We are satisfied with this balance as it reduces volatility.

Indeed if we reach the extreme case where $n_{buy} = 1$ and $n_{sell} = 201$:

$$ portfolio\_overperf(d) \approx overperf(s_{long}, d) - 0 $$

where $s_{long}$ is the longed stock. The portfolio becomes effectively as volatile as one stock.

These plots give insights on:

  1. Which are the features that are relevant to pick stocks?
  2. How their relevance evolves through time?

We can note that:

  1. The volatility features are dominant, the last price and volume features are used and the realized performance features are almost never used.
  2. The coefficients change through time and even change sign.

The first point shows a weakness in our choice of features as 4 features end up almost unused.

VI - Conclusion¶

VI - A) Summary¶

  • We implemented an equal weight long short strategy based on a linear regression investment signal, computed using different lookback periods.

  • The corresponding strategies failed to produce consistent returns during the testing period.

  • The analysis showed that long and short positions were relatively balanced through time which reduced portfolio volatility

  • Linear regression weights show that some features remained mostly unused during the testing period.

VI - B) Amelioration prospects¶

I believe there are many ways to improve on this work. Given more time I would have looked into the following remarks.

Regarding Features:

The strategy we showcased significantly depends on the choice of features. One systematic approach could have been to find a systematic way to generate features from price and volume using different parameters, the same way we created 3 volatility features.

We would create many features and then come to select a few of them using regularized models or subset selection methods. Features could be more thouroughly analysed for correlation or seasonality for instance as a way to reduce the number of features.

Regarding the Model:

The standard linear regression model we used was mainly chosen for the sake of simplicity. Indeed, its solution is computationnaly cheap and there are no hyper-parameters to fit. For instance, ridge regularisation would have required to test results for various penalisation factors.

Other models like XGBoost are popular in data science contests thanks to their high accuracy. These underlying algorithms are less simple and less interpretable. They also require many hyper-parameters to be optimised. I reckoned they were less appropriate for exploratory analysis.

Regarding computation efficiency:

The (computational) bottleneck of this notebook is the computations of $\hat{y}$ and the backtest. The main reason for this is the compounded loops which are very inefficient in native python as the interpreter has to interpret every loop iteration.

This could be avoided using a JIT compiler like numba for instance. This would dramatically reduce the computing time at the expense of code clarity. Indeed numba does not allow for pandas data structures. Numba must also be able to infer types of all variables which makes numba coding a bit rigid and time consuming.
